day in the garden?

00:03:53.610 --> 00:03:56.040
And that's often--
it's thought about,

00:03:56.040 --> 00:03:59.195
but it's not given
enough attention.

00:03:59.195 --> 00:04:01.320
So what you're thinking
about is, what do you like?

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:02.310
What's your lifestyle?

00:04:02.310 --> 00:04:05.740
How do you spend
time in the garden?

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:07.950
Who are you on a personal level?

00:04:07.950 --> 00:04:10.440
Do you have kids, pets?

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:12.210
Do you read or write sports?

00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:14.060
So they're all incredibly
important elements

00:04:14.060 --> 00:04:16.560
to consider when you go about
designing any kind of a space,

00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:19.170
because that's kind of who
you are from a lifestyle

00:04:19.170 --> 00:04:20.540
perspective.

00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:23.154
But when I started
writing my book,

00:04:23.154 --> 00:04:25.320
I kind of realized that a
lot of garden design books

00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:27.050
go straight into that.

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:28.570
And yes, that's
really important,

00:04:28.570 --> 00:04:31.460
but there's something else
which is really important

00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:34.920
and which often does get
completely forgotten about.

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:36.660
And that's your
dreams for the space.

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:39.690
And a few people were
like, oh, your dreams.

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:40.200
Why?

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:41.790
Why do you have to
dream and all that?

00:04:41.790 --> 00:04:43.890
You can just say, I
want that nice garden.

00:04:43.890 --> 00:04:46.950
And again, probably, because
my mom's a psychotherapist,

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:49.290
I like to take that step
back and just think, no.

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:52.770
It's good to dream, and
it's good to open your mind

00:04:52.770 --> 00:04:55.260
before you start going into
detail and into functions

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:57.120
and clotheslines
and compost bins

00:04:57.120 --> 00:04:59.730
and all that stuff, which has
nothing to do with dreams.

00:04:59.730 --> 00:05:02.020
It's just practical in function.

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:05.970
So in this instance, your
dreams are your vision

00:05:05.970 --> 00:05:08.050
of your perfect space.

00:05:08.050 --> 00:05:11.580
So gardens are
intensely personal,

00:05:11.580 --> 00:05:12.810
just like interior design is.

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:17.120
They're part of you, part of
your home in the best scenario.

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:19.054
They're extensions
of your living space.

00:05:19.054 --> 00:05:21.470
And that's why I think it's
really important to kind of go

00:05:21.470 --> 00:05:24.440
into that in a
little bit of detail

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:27.200
before you start looking at
practicalities and functions

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:29.040
and things like that.

00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:33.036
So they're different from
your functional requirements,

00:05:33.036 --> 00:05:34.910
because they're personal,
and they're made up

00:05:34.910 --> 00:05:38.300
of memories of times you've
spent in gardens, where you

00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:42.800
felt amazing or just, say, your
grandmother's garden, where you

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:45.140
have a memory, a personal
connection to the past

00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:47.640
or to people.

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:51.650
So there's a lot more to
it than just dreaming up

00:05:51.650 --> 00:05:53.600
a nice little space.

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:55.762
But one massive thing,
even if you have a balcony,

00:05:55.762 --> 00:05:58.220
even if you have a very small
patio, one thing I always say

00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:01.949
is at this stage, dream big.

00:06:01.949 --> 00:06:03.740
And I know you're not
going to have the Taj

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:07.730
Mahal on your balcony or
in a small patio space,

00:06:07.730 --> 00:06:11.180
but you can take elements
of the biggest dream

00:06:11.180 --> 00:06:14.670
that you can possibly have and
condense those elements down.

00:06:14.670 --> 00:06:17.900
And there is an exercise
in my book, which

00:06:17.900 --> 00:06:20.660
is called a Dream
Gardens Diagram, which

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:24.100
is just based around identifying
what it is you love about that.

00:06:24.100 --> 00:06:25.940
So if you were looking
at that, and that

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:28.610
was the space that you
choose for the exercise,

00:06:28.610 --> 00:06:31.112
then you can zoom
in on certain areas

00:06:31.112 --> 00:06:32.570
and say, well, I
love the symmetry.

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:35.390
I love the detail of
the filigree work.

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:36.390
I love the planting.

00:06:36.390 --> 00:06:39.235
I love the water, the
reflections, the calm,

00:06:39.235 --> 00:06:39.860
whatever it is.

00:06:39.860 --> 00:06:42.140
You can pull all those
together, and they

00:06:42.140 --> 00:06:44.810
can become your concept.

00:06:44.810 --> 00:06:47.760
So at this stage,
there are no limits.

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:50.712
And again, every time I
go into somebody's space,

00:06:50.712 --> 00:06:52.670
they start going, OK,
and now I need the patio,

00:06:52.670 --> 00:06:56.110
and now I need that, and I need
a circulation route to here.

00:06:56.110 --> 00:06:59.315
And I always have to stop people
and go, no, just go back to--

00:06:59.315 --> 00:07:01.490
be completely mad for
a while before you

00:07:01.490 --> 00:07:04.080
start getting practical.

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:05.324
So there is no--

00:07:05.324 --> 00:07:06.740
there are no limits
at this stage,

00:07:06.740 --> 00:07:11.857
just dreaming up
your perfect space.

00:07:11.857 --> 00:07:14.190
I never know why I include
this one, but for some reason

00:07:14.190 --> 00:07:16.760
it always makes me zoom
out a bit in my own head.

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:18.770
So I've left it in
just for the sake

00:07:18.770 --> 00:07:22.580
of kind of underlining that
idea of zooming out and not

00:07:22.580 --> 00:07:28.130
getting into the nitty gritty
of detail at this point.

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:30.860
So the exercise that
I have in the book

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:34.440
is really based on just a
memory of a place, where

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:35.690
you were really, really happy.

00:07:35.690 --> 00:07:38.270
So thinking of a garden
that you visited,

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:41.570
or a memory that you have
of having been in a garden,

00:07:41.570 --> 00:07:44.300
and it doesn't even need
to be perfectly designed.

00:07:44.300 --> 00:07:47.090
It can be completely wild
meadowscape or anything

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:49.180
like that.

00:07:49.180 --> 00:07:51.650
And basically, what
you're doing is

00:07:51.650 --> 00:07:55.460
you're thinking about what made
that space feel so good to you.

00:07:55.460 --> 00:07:59.690
Why was it-- why did you have
a personal connection to it?

00:07:59.690 --> 00:08:00.334
Was it the fun?

00:08:00.334 --> 00:08:01.250
Was it the symmetries?

00:08:01.250 --> 00:08:01.760
The wildness?

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:02.260
The dramas?

00:08:02.260 --> 00:08:04.070
So each space-- and
that's something

00:08:04.070 --> 00:08:06.800
you guys can do later on, if you
want, or take the books home,

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:09.644
and it's all kind of
outlined in that, too.

00:08:09.644 --> 00:08:11.060
And it's a really
good-- it sounds

00:08:11.060 --> 00:08:13.040
like a very simple
exercise, but it's

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:16.340
a really good way of
allowing yourself to not

00:08:16.340 --> 00:08:17.940
design before you design.

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:19.700
So just going, oh,
I love that space.

00:08:19.700 --> 00:08:22.350
I really enjoyed that space.

00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:25.400
So this is my one,
unless somebody else

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:27.800
wants to give me one.

00:08:27.800 --> 00:08:30.990
I love the Alhambra
in the south of Spain,

00:08:30.990 --> 00:08:35.544
which is an amazing, absolutely
amazing garden and palace.

00:08:35.544 --> 00:08:36.710
And they're Moorish gardens.

00:08:36.710 --> 00:08:38.710
They're really symmetrical,
but yet the planting

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:40.220
is really wild and free.

00:08:40.220 --> 00:08:42.080
So I love that
combination of those kind

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:45.590
of perfect architecture
and then the wild planting.

00:08:45.590 --> 00:08:48.200
So for me, it was the
timeless feel of it--

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:50.909
the balance, the water, the
wild planting, the harmony.

00:08:50.909 --> 00:08:51.950
And this is the exercise.

00:08:51.950 --> 00:08:55.045
What you're doing is a
simple sketch spider diagram,

00:08:55.045 --> 00:08:57.170
and you're putting the
characteristics of the space

00:08:57.170 --> 00:08:59.450
above and the moods below.

00:08:59.450 --> 00:09:01.160
So the moods of
this space actually

00:09:01.160 --> 00:09:04.630
become your concept
of your garden design.

00:09:04.630 --> 00:09:06.380
So you need to think,
right, that's what I

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:08.570
want to bring to my own space.

00:09:08.570 --> 00:09:11.150
And even if it is a
balcony, there's balance.

00:09:11.150 --> 00:09:11.879
There's calm.

00:09:11.879 --> 00:09:12.920
You want to feel at ease.

00:09:12.920 --> 00:09:14.450
You want to feel happier.

00:09:14.450 --> 00:09:16.010
You want to feel freer.

00:09:16.010 --> 00:09:18.770
If, say, you went for a meadow
that you felt incredibly

00:09:18.770 --> 00:09:21.050
happy in and a
memory that you have,

00:09:21.050 --> 00:09:23.450
there's so many ways of
bringing elements of a meadow--

00:09:23.450 --> 00:09:27.860
the movement of the grasses,
looking at the wide, open sky.

00:09:27.860 --> 00:09:30.110
Why not try and create
something that kind of emulates

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:34.940
that feeling, even if it is a
tiny balcony or a small patio?

00:09:34.940 --> 00:09:39.830
So really, that's just about
taking those and bringing them

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:40.890
into your concept.

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:44.360
So for me, it was the
Alhambra, creating

00:09:44.360 --> 00:09:49.640
a calm space inspired
by a Moorish palace,

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:50.940
yet the planting is wild.

00:09:50.940 --> 00:09:52.940
So there's not too much
perfection going on,

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:55.900
which can become
boring, and you're never

00:09:55.900 --> 00:09:59.900
going to actually be able to
achieve and maintain anyway.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:02.300
So that's your
new found concept.

00:10:02.300 --> 00:10:05.960
So that was my scenario
there-- a calm space inspired

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:08.559
by the Alhambra gardens in Spain
with wild, natural planting,

00:10:08.559 --> 00:10:10.100
plenty of water,
and a timeless feel.

00:10:10.100 --> 00:10:12.350
So really simple but
there's so many elements

00:10:12.350 --> 00:10:15.130
then that you can choose,
pick out, and build

00:10:15.130 --> 00:10:16.210
into your design.

00:10:16.210 --> 00:10:19.360
So that informs your materials,
your colors, your water

00:10:19.360 --> 00:10:20.380
features.

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:23.050
It's easy then, because
I think a lot of people

00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:24.770
don't know where to start.

00:10:24.770 --> 00:10:28.120
So this is a great way of
kind of identifying a concept

00:10:28.120 --> 00:10:30.130
and then going, right,
the paving I need to get

00:10:30.130 --> 00:10:32.740
needs to match that feel, and
the water needs to match that,

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:36.380
and everything needs to follow
that feel and underline that.

00:10:36.380 --> 00:10:38.590
And then a concept of the
garden works naturally,

00:10:38.590 --> 00:10:42.130
and it's not disjointed.

00:10:42.130 --> 00:10:45.920
So the next part is
Form Follows Function,

00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:48.060
which Louis Sullivan said.

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:55.740
And as you guys know, within the
internet, you go into a page,

00:10:55.740 --> 00:10:57.930
it doesn't work, you're
gone immediately.

00:10:57.930 --> 00:11:01.140
So the same thing applies
to a badly designed garden.

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:03.600
If it's badly designed,
if it doesn't work,

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:06.320
never mind the look or
the beauty or whatever.

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:09.040
It can be beautiful, but if it
doesn't work, it's annoying,

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:11.730
and you just don't want
to be in the space.

00:11:11.730 --> 00:11:17.430
So basically, our gardens, from
a tangible perspective, are--

00:11:17.430 --> 00:11:19.890
they're spaces for living,
and they need to work.

00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:22.720
It's really simple.

00:11:22.720 --> 00:11:26.280
And the first thing I get my
clients to do is do out a list,

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:26.780
and--

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:29.650
I'm sorry, the second
thing after dreaming.

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.450
Get them to do a
list of how they

00:11:32.450 --> 00:11:33.700
spend their day in the garden.

00:11:33.700 --> 00:11:35.420
So basically how they--

00:11:35.420 --> 00:11:36.640
the most boring stuff--

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:37.997
I hang my washing out.

00:11:37.997 --> 00:11:38.830
The dog goes around.

00:11:38.830 --> 00:11:43.190
The kids go to the trampoline,
all of those kind of things.

00:11:43.190 --> 00:11:45.820
But also to say, I
like to entertain.

00:11:45.820 --> 00:11:48.300
So it'd be nice to have a
pool to dangle our legs in,

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:49.060
et cetera.

00:11:49.060 --> 00:11:51.160
That's us at the Bloom garden
this year dangling our legs.

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:52.201
So I had to include that.

00:11:55.250 --> 00:11:58.354
So that's just really
an idea of what

00:11:58.354 --> 00:12:00.520
your day looks like in the
garden and all the things

00:12:00.520 --> 00:12:04.600
the garden needs to function
for you. [? Like, ?]

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:09.040
So the functions of the
garden, and then the list

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:10.480
of functional requirements.

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:11.080
That's it.

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:13.390
Basically, really
simple, really easy.

00:12:13.390 --> 00:12:15.900
List out everything you
need in the actual garden,

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:19.026
and it doesn't need
to be super detailed.

00:12:19.026 --> 00:12:20.650
But you need this
because the next step

00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:21.952
is putting it onto paper.

00:12:21.952 --> 00:12:23.410
And when you put
it onto paper, you

00:12:23.410 --> 00:12:25.420
need to take off each and
every single one of those.

00:12:25.420 --> 00:12:27.336
And if one of them is
missing, then the garden

00:12:27.336 --> 00:12:28.485
is not going to work 100%.

00:12:31.220 --> 00:12:35.140
So that was a client of mine
in Strand Hill and Sligo.

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:36.464
The job was kind of half done.

00:12:36.464 --> 00:12:37.630
The builder's still outside.

00:12:37.630 --> 00:12:39.400
The dog, which they
weren't supposed

00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:41.650
to have a dog-- the whole
garden was based around them

00:12:41.650 --> 00:12:43.240
not having kids or a dog.

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:45.830
They now have a child and a dog.

00:12:45.830 --> 00:12:47.770
And he destroyed
the garden, but this

00:12:47.770 --> 00:12:50.050
was before we did the garden.

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:54.055
And you can see there's nothing
there, and it looks horrendous.

00:12:54.055 --> 00:12:55.180
The house is getting there.

00:12:55.180 --> 00:13:00.730
Everything is brilliant, but a
lot of spaces that you see you

00:13:00.730 --> 00:13:02.860
have to assess really,
really well in order

00:13:02.860 --> 00:13:04.690
to get the design right.

00:13:04.690 --> 00:13:08.410
So you're looking at everything
from soil samples, aspect,

00:13:08.410 --> 00:13:09.790
garden climate--

00:13:09.790 --> 00:13:13.320
probably pretty boring at this
stage, but it's so important.

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:15.707
So even if you have
a small balcony,

00:13:15.707 --> 00:13:17.290
you need to make
sure that you address

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:22.540
things like wind,
privacy, views to make

00:13:22.540 --> 00:13:24.670
sure you don't make any
mistakes and then end up

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:26.890
with the neighbor
right there looking in

00:13:26.890 --> 00:13:30.882
at you, even though you wanted
this enclosed private haven.

00:13:30.882 --> 00:13:33.340
So there are things you need
to list out at the very start.

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:37.102
Obviously, for bigger sites,
it gets a lot more complicated,

00:13:37.102 --> 00:13:38.560
and you need to
put in more detail.

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:40.750
Sometimes we get
surveyors in, because it's

00:13:40.750 --> 00:13:43.880
too detailed to do with slopes
and all that kind of stuff.

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:47.240
But for small spaces, it's
relatively easy to do.

00:13:47.240 --> 00:13:49.300
The main thing-- common sense.

00:13:49.300 --> 00:13:51.250
You're looking at views.

00:13:51.250 --> 00:13:52.070
Does it have light?

00:13:52.070 --> 00:13:55.200
So you're looking at the
strengths of the space.

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:56.770
And how can you enhance them?

00:13:56.770 --> 00:13:58.550
That's really important.

00:13:58.550 --> 00:14:00.730
And then you're also
looking at the challenges.

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:05.410
So you can see the two there.

00:14:05.410 --> 00:14:09.280
We do a show called RT Super
Garden, and pretty much all

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:14.080
the gardens we go into look
like that-- absolute disasters.

00:14:14.080 --> 00:14:18.610
And after the show leaves,
then they're ta-da.

00:14:18.610 --> 00:14:19.240
Yeah, right.

00:14:19.240 --> 00:14:22.030
Five weeks later,
blood, sweat, and tears.

00:14:22.030 --> 00:14:25.450
But yeah, that's actually
the joy of it anyway.

00:14:25.450 --> 00:14:29.050
It's television, transformation,
and we all love that.

00:14:29.050 --> 00:14:31.130
But as I say, nothing
is unsolvable.

00:14:31.130 --> 00:14:34.390
And the main thing is having
that vision and the dream

00:14:34.390 --> 00:14:35.350
for what is to come.

00:14:35.350 --> 00:14:37.480
And I think some
people find that easier

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:39.910
than others to imagine.

00:14:39.910 --> 00:14:43.600
Like my mom cannot imagine
what a garden will look like.

00:14:43.600 --> 00:14:49.255
She's like, how can you even
visualize how it will be?

00:14:49.255 --> 00:14:51.140
Yeah, probably
because I studied it.

00:14:53.996 --> 00:14:55.870
So yeah, it's all about
building on strengths

00:14:55.870 --> 00:15:00.810
and overcoming challenges in
gardens and garden design.

00:15:00.810 --> 00:15:03.490
Site measurements-- I touched
on that briefly just there.

00:15:03.490 --> 00:15:04.990
It can be incredibly
complicated,

00:15:04.990 --> 00:15:08.230
and it can be very, very simple
to just doing a scaled sketch,

00:15:08.230 --> 00:15:10.420
putting in your sizes,
your heights, and where

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:14.985
the entrance, exit,
where the pathways are.

00:15:14.985 --> 00:15:17.110
And then the first thing
is getting the site right.

00:15:17.110 --> 00:15:19.990
It's doing a very
simple scale sketch

00:15:19.990 --> 00:15:22.115
and exploring what's
happening on the site.

00:15:22.115 --> 00:15:23.740
So I'm not going to
go into big detail,

00:15:23.740 --> 00:15:25.600
because that is actually boring.

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:28.060
But it's good to know,
and it's detailed

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:30.340
in the book as well
just to know that that's

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:31.900
how you have to
start if you want

00:15:31.900 --> 00:15:35.200
to take on a plot of
any considerable size.

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:41.740
Which actually that's kind of
a realistic, large city garden

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:43.750
that you could kind of
measure out yourself

00:15:43.750 --> 00:15:46.960
as opposed to getting
somebody in to do it for you.

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:49.420
So after that comes the
functional layout plan,

00:15:49.420 --> 00:15:52.060
which is basically taking
the functions-- so what

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:55.840
the garden has to do for you
and plunking them on the plan.

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:56.770
And they're bubbles.

00:15:56.770 --> 00:15:57.820
They're not designed.

00:15:57.820 --> 00:15:58.736
They're not beautiful.

00:15:58.736 --> 00:15:59.890
They're not details.

00:15:59.890 --> 00:16:03.520
They're basically sketched
bubbles telling you

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:05.140
exactly what happens on site.

00:16:05.140 --> 00:16:08.200
So where you need privacy,
where you want a patio,

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:12.560
where you want screening,
where you need a wind screen.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:15.042
So all the things that you
looked at that were challenges

00:16:15.042 --> 00:16:16.750
need to be addressed
on this in a bubble.

00:16:16.750 --> 00:16:19.000
So it doesn't need to represent
the shape or anything.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.160
So it's actually
really easy to do.

00:16:22.160 --> 00:16:23.860
But it's so
informative to when you

00:16:23.860 --> 00:16:25.510
start going to sketch
detail, and you

00:16:25.510 --> 00:16:30.040
start putting in details in it.

00:16:30.040 --> 00:16:32.980
So that brings me to
the bigger picture--

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:36.040
great design, quite far
away from the bubbles.

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:37.890
This is one of my
favorite pictures.

00:16:37.890 --> 00:16:41.050
It's Tom Stuart-Smith,
who's a UK-based designer.

00:16:41.050 --> 00:16:43.600
And it's just such
a beautiful picture,

00:16:43.600 --> 00:16:46.540
because it shows how a garden
can blend into the landscape

00:16:46.540 --> 00:16:48.790
beyond without-- it
just feels like it's

00:16:48.790 --> 00:16:51.670
a part of the landscape.

00:16:51.670 --> 00:16:53.870
And I'll go back to
that in a minute.

00:16:53.870 --> 00:16:59.890
So what makes good design,
and are we born designers?

00:16:59.890 --> 00:17:01.570
It's an interesting
question, because I

00:17:01.570 --> 00:17:03.970
don't think we're
necessarily born designers.

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:06.280
Some people are better
at it than others,

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:08.740
but it's definitely
something you can learn.

00:17:08.740 --> 00:17:11.500
And what does help-- and
I'm sure a lot of you guys

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:15.700
are design-based or
from design backgrounds.

00:17:15.700 --> 00:17:19.240
So you'd be aware of a lot of
these principles, and the fact

00:17:19.240 --> 00:17:21.730
that they do kind of
influence everything from car

00:17:21.730 --> 00:17:25.240
design to pen
design to everything

00:17:25.240 --> 00:17:26.859
has those principles.

00:17:26.859 --> 00:17:30.480
And again, it goes back to
what works and functions.

00:17:30.480 --> 00:17:33.660
It goes back to the
principles of these four

00:17:33.660 --> 00:17:36.210
and then another one
I'll talk about after.

00:17:36.210 --> 00:17:37.890
The first one we'll
look at briefly

00:17:37.890 --> 00:17:40.080
is the unity and
harmony, and we'll

00:17:40.080 --> 00:17:42.510
talk about it just
in the garden setting

00:17:42.510 --> 00:17:45.219
and how it works with the house,
the garden, and the setting.

00:17:45.219 --> 00:17:47.010
And that's the picture
I showed you before.

00:17:47.010 --> 00:17:50.010
This is the same one in
winter at the bottom.

00:17:50.010 --> 00:17:53.230
Again, Tom Stuart-Smith
in the top one, too,

00:17:53.230 --> 00:17:56.787
and it just shows how
the house, first of all,

00:17:56.787 --> 00:17:57.870
is linked with the garden.

00:17:57.870 --> 00:17:59.460
You can see the
colors, the textures,

00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:02.370
pick up on the red brick,
the grasses, and the water,

00:18:02.370 --> 00:18:03.270
and the sizes.

00:18:03.270 --> 00:18:05.340
So you've got a connection
between the house

00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:07.590
and the garden,
the design space.

00:18:07.590 --> 00:18:11.310
And then beyond that you have a
connection of the design garden

00:18:11.310 --> 00:18:12.540
with the landscape beyond.

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:15.000
So in the landscape
beyond, for example, you've

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.180
got darker spots of big trees.

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:22.100
And Tom's brought that into
the foreground of the garden

00:18:22.100 --> 00:18:25.110
by having darker shapes, the
topiary shapes in the front,

00:18:25.110 --> 00:18:27.800
and then the lighter
ponds, which kind of echo

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:29.280
what's going on behind.

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:31.275
So that creates
unity and harmony,

00:18:31.275 --> 00:18:33.150
because you're blending
all of that together.

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:38.610
Simplicity-- I mean
the Persian gardens are

00:18:38.610 --> 00:18:41.310
a huge influence
for me and I think

00:18:41.310 --> 00:18:43.590
are a great example
of simplicity.

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:45.420
Less is more, and
I think that really

00:18:45.420 --> 00:18:48.660
applies to online as well.

00:18:48.660 --> 00:18:51.980
There's so much being
chucked at you all the time

00:18:51.980 --> 00:18:56.340
that it's really nice to have a
calm, simple design sometimes.

00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:58.860
There's nothing I like more
than looking at a website that's

00:18:58.860 --> 00:19:00.480
just like, ah, calm.

00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:04.920
Not too many ads, not too many
things being thrown at you.

00:19:04.920 --> 00:19:07.980
But of course, there has
to be a balance, which

00:19:07.980 --> 00:19:10.020
brings me to now.

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:12.750
It should bring me to
balance, really, shouldn't it?

00:19:12.750 --> 00:19:15.480
Scale and proportion.

00:19:15.480 --> 00:19:18.006
So really the same
thing as the links

00:19:18.006 --> 00:19:19.380
between the house
and the setting

00:19:19.380 --> 00:19:21.434
and the views beyond the garden.

00:19:21.434 --> 00:19:23.100
It's the relationship
between the house.

00:19:23.100 --> 00:19:25.560
So you don't want the house
to be absolutely gigantic

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:27.110
and the person to
feel really small.

00:19:27.110 --> 00:19:29.160
Same thing with
planting-- so trees

00:19:29.160 --> 00:19:33.000
can't be tiny and the house
really big or vice versa.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.250
So there's got to be a
relationship between everything

00:19:35.250 --> 00:19:37.800
that's happening in the
space, the landscape beyond.

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:41.610
And then also, obviously, the
house and the person because we

00:19:41.610 --> 00:19:47.255
can't forget that it's you
that's experiencing that space.

00:19:47.255 --> 00:19:48.630
And the best way
of doing that is

00:19:48.630 --> 00:19:53.160
to start sketching or thinking
in 3-D as opposed to 2-D

00:19:53.160 --> 00:19:54.420
flat way.

00:19:54.420 --> 00:19:56.720
There's Alice.

00:19:56.720 --> 00:19:59.670
And there's balance.

00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:03.120
So balance is really all about
everything coming together

00:20:03.120 --> 00:20:06.530
in a pleasing composition,
and there's so much--

00:20:06.530 --> 00:20:10.440
that work that comes into that
from all the other things we

00:20:10.440 --> 00:20:12.670
looked at-- scale
and proportion.

00:20:12.670 --> 00:20:15.150
It's actually really
easy to get balance

00:20:15.150 --> 00:20:17.070
right when you have
a symmetrical garden,

00:20:17.070 --> 00:20:19.080
so the likes of the Alhambra.

00:20:19.080 --> 00:20:20.910
If you take that as
inspiration, it's

00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:22.660
quite easy to get it
right, because you've

00:20:22.660 --> 00:20:24.270
got that inherent symmetry.

00:20:24.270 --> 00:20:28.377
Whilst if you kind of push it to
being asymmetrical, the design,

00:20:28.377 --> 00:20:30.960
it does get a little bit harder,
because you need to make sure

00:20:30.960 --> 00:20:33.474
you get the balance of the
forms, the shapes, the sizes,

00:20:33.474 --> 00:20:34.390
and all of that right.

00:20:34.390 --> 00:20:37.470
So it does get a
little bit trickier.

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:41.370
You'll also have mystery,
excitement, light and darkness,

00:20:41.370 --> 00:20:44.670
balance and color,
and structures also

00:20:44.670 --> 00:20:47.685
need to be balanced.

00:20:47.685 --> 00:20:49.060
So there are great
ways, I think,

00:20:49.060 --> 00:20:51.160
to start looking at design.

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:55.240
I don't know what percentage
of you guys are design-based

00:20:55.240 --> 00:20:56.780
or have a background in design.

00:20:56.780 --> 00:20:59.770
So I should have probably
asked that at the start.

00:20:59.770 --> 00:21:03.850
I'm sure you're aware of some
of these or most of these,

00:21:03.850 --> 00:21:06.430
but they're a great thing to
even-- even if you do know,

00:21:06.430 --> 00:21:07.720
and you're aware of them--

00:21:07.720 --> 00:21:11.840
to make sure you remind yourself
of on a kind of regular basis.

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:15.610
The other thing that I always
find fascinating to look at

00:21:15.610 --> 00:21:16.640
is the golden ratio.

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:19.270
And again, you're
probably all aware of it,

00:21:19.270 --> 00:21:22.030
but I find it quite
interesting in garden design,

00:21:22.030 --> 00:21:26.140
because you're looking at
nature to inform nature.

00:21:26.140 --> 00:21:32.495
So from ferns and the way
they grow to succulents.

00:21:32.495 --> 00:21:34.120
There was actually
a garden at Chelsea,

00:21:34.120 --> 00:21:38.080
which was based all around
the mathematics of geometry,

00:21:38.080 --> 00:21:40.380
which had the succulent
on the right there.

00:21:40.380 --> 00:21:42.670
It had a lot of those
kind of shapes and forms,

00:21:42.670 --> 00:21:44.860
and the mathematics
behind it are just--

00:21:44.860 --> 00:21:46.930
I don't do math.

00:21:46.930 --> 00:21:49.849
To me, it's absolutely
baffling, but it's incredible.

00:21:49.849 --> 00:21:52.265
It's really inspiring to look
at and to apply to projects.

00:21:55.120 --> 00:21:57.240
And the fact that
it's also found

00:21:57.240 --> 00:21:59.840
in our bodies, and the
fact that it repeats,

00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:02.320
and it's just incredible.

00:22:02.320 --> 00:22:03.820
I find it really,
really interesting

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:05.236
that when you
clench your fist, it

00:22:05.236 --> 00:22:08.790
forms into a perfect
golden ratio curl.

00:22:08.790 --> 00:22:09.900
But that can inform--

00:22:09.900 --> 00:22:15.100
that does and can inform
a huge amount of design.

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:17.530
And I very cheekily stuck
it on top of Google.

00:22:17.530 --> 00:22:20.980
So I don't know if that actually
does, but it kind of works.

00:22:20.980 --> 00:22:23.710
But it works in garden
design, the Apple logo.

00:22:23.710 --> 00:22:25.570
So that's-- car design
and everything--

00:22:25.570 --> 00:22:27.290
it kind of influences
everything.

00:22:27.290 --> 00:22:29.230
And the reason
for that is really

00:22:29.230 --> 00:22:33.370
because we're using what is
inherently found in nature,

00:22:33.370 --> 00:22:34.630
and that's informing design.

00:22:34.630 --> 00:22:36.490
So it's an interesting cycle.

00:22:39.220 --> 00:22:42.749
So the next thing is choosing
shapes for the garden.

00:22:42.749 --> 00:22:45.040
So we've gone and looked at
the functions of the garden

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:48.760
and putting that in in
bubbles and how it works

00:22:48.760 --> 00:22:51.010
and how we make sure
everything is included that you

00:22:51.010 --> 00:22:52.960
want and need in the garden.

00:22:52.960 --> 00:22:57.700
And the next bit is how to
actually put that into a plan

00:22:57.700 --> 00:22:59.190
that you can work from.

00:22:59.190 --> 00:23:03.537
And personally, I go
through the same thing,

00:23:03.537 --> 00:23:05.870
and I recognized this a couple
of years ago when I went,

00:23:05.870 --> 00:23:07.036
OK, that's what's happening.

00:23:07.036 --> 00:23:10.630
I go through the
same kind of problem

00:23:10.630 --> 00:23:12.010
every time I have a design job.

00:23:12.010 --> 00:23:14.650
I start off going, this
is going to be amazing.

00:23:14.650 --> 00:23:16.330
It's going to be
such a good project.

00:23:16.330 --> 00:23:17.990
And then I start sketching,
and I start doing stuff.

00:23:17.990 --> 00:23:19.870
And I'm like, oh, my god,
it's going to be a disaster.

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:21.036
It's going to be horrendous.

00:23:21.036 --> 00:23:22.390
The client is going to hate us.

00:23:22.390 --> 00:23:23.980
And then I start
doing more on it

00:23:23.980 --> 00:23:26.130
and force myself through that,
and I come out the other end

00:23:26.130 --> 00:23:27.350
and go, OK, it's
going to be fine.

00:23:27.350 --> 00:23:28.030
It'll be great.

00:23:28.030 --> 00:23:29.275
It'll be good.

00:23:29.275 --> 00:23:31.400
So I think a huge amount
of people go through that.

00:23:31.400 --> 00:23:33.340
I think designers
in general always

00:23:33.340 --> 00:23:35.685
go through that kind
of stage of self-doubt.

00:23:35.685 --> 00:23:38.590
And the hardest part is
actually this, which, for me,

00:23:38.590 --> 00:23:40.870
personally, is
putting the shapes

00:23:40.870 --> 00:23:44.560
and making decisions as opposed
to just messing and playing.

00:23:44.560 --> 00:23:48.820
So I was happy when I
learned that it is actually

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:50.110
very easy to do.

00:23:50.110 --> 00:23:52.750
That basically you take
the functional layout plan

00:23:52.750 --> 00:23:57.460
with the bubbles, and you sketch
over that with either a layout

00:23:57.460 --> 00:23:59.440
paper or a tracing paper.

00:23:59.440 --> 00:24:02.140
And you just explore
the shapes based on what

00:24:02.140 --> 00:24:03.520
you have from those bubbles.

00:24:03.520 --> 00:24:05.920
Because you know you want
the patio at the back door,

00:24:05.920 --> 00:24:08.410
because that's where you want
to go from the kitchen, where

00:24:08.410 --> 00:24:09.470
the door is.

00:24:09.470 --> 00:24:10.720
So you know you want it there.

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:12.136
You just need to
decide on shapes.

00:24:12.136 --> 00:24:14.330
You need to decide how
they link to each other.

00:24:14.330 --> 00:24:17.225
So you've already made a lot of
decisions without knowing it.

00:24:17.225 --> 00:24:19.100
You've placed the patio
where it wants to go.

00:24:19.100 --> 00:24:22.840
You've put the
trampoline where you can

00:24:22.840 --> 00:24:24.760
see the kids from the kitchen.

00:24:24.760 --> 00:24:26.800
You've done all of
that background work

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:28.270
without realizing.

00:24:28.270 --> 00:24:31.570
So you just explore, and
you start looking at shapes

00:24:31.570 --> 00:24:34.780
and what works.

00:24:34.780 --> 00:24:35.830
I can see the square.

00:24:35.830 --> 00:24:40.270
It's free-form,
circles, combination.

00:24:40.270 --> 00:24:42.700
You can have completely
free-form shapes.

00:24:42.700 --> 00:24:46.240
It's really what appeals to
you and mostly, actually,

00:24:46.240 --> 00:24:48.280
what your concept wants.

00:24:48.280 --> 00:24:52.990
So if you have a very
loose meadow-style garden,

00:24:52.990 --> 00:24:55.180
and you want it to
feel really wild,

00:24:55.180 --> 00:24:57.200
then unless you're
doing it on purpose,

00:24:57.200 --> 00:25:01.004
you're not going to produce
large concrete slabs, which

00:25:01.004 --> 00:25:02.170
I actually love the idea of.

00:25:02.170 --> 00:25:05.260
But then you'd be breaking
those rules for a reason

00:25:05.260 --> 00:25:07.630
if that's what you wanted to do.

00:25:07.630 --> 00:25:09.610
So it depends on
what the concept

00:25:09.610 --> 00:25:12.447
is to make it work for you.

00:25:12.447 --> 00:25:14.530
And then after that, if
you've chosen your shapes,

00:25:14.530 --> 00:25:17.642
you've decided where everything
goes, comes the really, really

00:25:17.642 --> 00:25:19.600
exciting part, because
you've got your concept.

00:25:19.600 --> 00:25:22.127
You know how it's
supposed to feel,

00:25:22.127 --> 00:25:23.710
and you get to play
around, basically,

00:25:23.710 --> 00:25:28.120
with materials,
colors, planting,

00:25:28.120 --> 00:25:30.260
and it just all
follows your concept.

00:25:30.260 --> 00:25:32.509
So in my case, if
it's the Alhambra--

00:25:32.509 --> 00:25:34.300
god, I'd love an Alhambra
garden, actually,

00:25:34.300 --> 00:25:35.950
now that I think about it.

00:25:35.950 --> 00:25:39.890
Don't Google my garden,
whatever you do.

00:25:39.890 --> 00:25:41.880
I don't know if technology
is that advanced yet

00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:43.191
to zoom in right down.

00:25:43.191 --> 00:25:43.690
Is it?

00:25:46.510 --> 00:25:48.840
It's in a mess.

00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:52.090
But basically, it all
comes down to your concept

00:25:52.090 --> 00:25:56.770
and how to bring that concept to
life through materials, colors,

00:25:56.770 --> 00:25:58.060
and planting.

00:25:58.060 --> 00:25:59.630
Is it really?

00:25:59.630 --> 00:26:03.272
Like, can you actually
see different plants?

00:26:03.272 --> 00:26:05.430
AUDIENCE: Let me
have your address.

00:26:05.430 --> 00:26:08.790
LEONIE CORNELIUS:
No, no, no, it's OK.

00:26:08.790 --> 00:26:09.570
