00:26:10.920 --> 00:26:12.600
That's crazy.

00:26:12.600 --> 00:26:14.790
I digress.

00:26:14.790 --> 00:26:17.460
So the concept--
again, that goes back

00:26:17.460 --> 00:26:19.590
to the idea of kind
of fleshing out

00:26:19.590 --> 00:26:22.410
the whole design
to suit your feel

00:26:22.410 --> 00:26:26.050
and to suit what your dream is.

00:26:26.050 --> 00:26:33.090
So if it was a seaside garden,
what do you bring into it?

00:26:33.090 --> 00:26:34.320
Do you bring in pebbles?

00:26:34.320 --> 00:26:36.990
And then also think-- and I
go into this in the book--

00:26:36.990 --> 00:26:39.900
don't be afraid to go for all
the materials that are expected

00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:41.730
and then take some out
and break the rules.

00:26:41.730 --> 00:26:43.590
And if it was a
seaside garden, it's

00:26:43.590 --> 00:26:45.990
pebbles and ropes and all that.

00:26:45.990 --> 00:26:48.660
Get rid of the ropes and
replace it with rusted metal,

00:26:48.660 --> 00:26:52.110
or get rid of the
expected pebble

00:26:52.110 --> 00:26:53.910
and replace it with concrete.

00:26:53.910 --> 00:26:55.840
Or do something that
makes it new and fresh

00:26:55.840 --> 00:26:59.234
and not the expected.

00:26:59.234 --> 00:27:00.900
I don't think I say
it there, but that's

00:27:00.900 --> 00:27:01.775
outlined in the book.

00:27:01.775 --> 00:27:03.240
And it's actually
a big part of, I

00:27:03.240 --> 00:27:06.540
think, what makes really good
garden design is breaking

00:27:06.540 --> 00:27:08.370
the rules once you
know them, once you

00:27:08.370 --> 00:27:11.350
know what you want to achieve.

00:27:11.350 --> 00:27:13.080
So being selective--
if you're going

00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:16.290
to go for colors and
materials, choose

00:27:16.290 --> 00:27:19.260
two colors, two strong colors
and two strong materials.

00:27:19.260 --> 00:27:23.885
Don't go mad, because you
want the concept to be really,

00:27:23.885 --> 00:27:25.260
really strong,
and you can always

00:27:25.260 --> 00:27:26.460
add little bits here and there.

00:27:26.460 --> 00:27:27.876
You can always
create little rooms

00:27:27.876 --> 00:27:30.180
that have separate feels,
but you can see it in this--

00:27:30.180 --> 00:27:33.450
the strength of that
rusted corten steel,

00:27:33.450 --> 00:27:35.580
and then picking up on
that tiny little planting

00:27:35.580 --> 00:27:41.310
bits in that same color
just balances so well.

00:27:41.310 --> 00:27:44.310
This one, again, you can see
the designer, Luciano Giubbilei,

00:27:44.310 --> 00:27:48.370
has chosen loads a kind
of neutral, muted tones.

00:27:48.370 --> 00:27:52.860
They're different colors but
loads of different materials.

00:27:52.860 --> 00:27:55.590
But they all work, because
they're all neutrals.

00:27:55.590 --> 00:27:59.280
So again, the palette is
really simple, really clean.

00:27:59.280 --> 00:28:03.750
Same designer-- again,
he loves neutrals.

00:28:03.750 --> 00:28:07.407
But it really allows structure
and form to jump out at you.

00:28:07.407 --> 00:28:09.240
While as if there was
too many colors there,

00:28:09.240 --> 00:28:10.698
you wouldn't see
those ball shapes.

00:28:10.698 --> 00:28:15.024
You wouldn't see the
multi-stem trees.

00:28:15.024 --> 00:28:16.440
And then this one,
Luis Barragan--

00:28:16.440 --> 00:28:19.580
he's a Mexican architect--

00:28:19.580 --> 00:28:22.500
so he chose loads of different
colors for the space,

00:28:22.500 --> 00:28:24.460
but he used one material.

00:28:24.460 --> 00:28:26.670
So the colors are--
there's plenty of color--

00:28:26.670 --> 00:28:28.980
the color of the
sky and the water

00:28:28.980 --> 00:28:31.680
and loads of colors
but the same material

00:28:31.680 --> 00:28:34.330
pretty much throughout.

00:28:34.330 --> 00:28:35.970
And then the last
slide is really

00:28:35.970 --> 00:28:39.420
to show that vegetable growing
can actually be pretty, too.

00:28:39.420 --> 00:28:43.510
It doesn't have to be
a kind of ugly plot.

00:28:43.510 --> 00:28:45.810
You can actually
use cool materials

00:28:45.810 --> 00:28:48.600
like the wicker and the
timber and the terracotta

00:28:48.600 --> 00:28:53.130
and make it really
colorful and pretty.

00:28:53.130 --> 00:28:56.430
So the last bit I'll go into
is the planting perfection,

00:28:56.430 --> 00:28:58.170
choosing planting.

00:28:58.170 --> 00:29:00.810
So again, the planting
that you choose

00:29:00.810 --> 00:29:03.250
needs to follow your concept.

00:29:03.250 --> 00:29:10.680
So if your concept is you
want a jungle haven in Ranola,

00:29:10.680 --> 00:29:13.020
you need to make sure all the
plants you choose not only

00:29:13.020 --> 00:29:15.280
work for Ireland,
work for the space,

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:18.700
but that they also
work for the concept.

00:29:18.700 --> 00:29:22.710
And so you study what works,
how the jungle looks--

00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:26.540
big leaves, the
foliage, the bamboo,

00:29:26.540 --> 00:29:28.500
and how to make that work.

00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:29.640
And it's totally workable.

00:29:29.640 --> 00:29:31.707
I just wrote an article
about that, actually,

00:29:31.707 --> 00:29:33.540
and it can work really,
really well and look

00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:36.624
really lush and jungle-like.

00:29:36.624 --> 00:29:38.040
And again, for the
planting, we're

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:40.440
also considering the
principles of design,

00:29:40.440 --> 00:29:42.000
which are really important.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:46.200
So one more thing is
right plant, right place.

00:29:46.200 --> 00:29:49.260
And it's really about a
huge amount of interest

00:29:49.260 --> 00:29:53.310
these days has been put
into creating sustainable

00:29:53.310 --> 00:29:56.820
gardens that grow themselves as
opposed to having to maintain

00:29:56.820 --> 00:29:59.820
all the time, and
it's really opened up

00:29:59.820 --> 00:30:04.470
a lot of new kind of
avenues for young designers,

00:30:04.470 --> 00:30:08.490
like Chelsea and Bloom and all
those places, where you're not

00:30:08.490 --> 00:30:12.419
stuck in kind of old traditions,
which don't work, really,

00:30:12.419 --> 00:30:13.960
unless you have huge
amounts of time.

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:15.584
So that's what we're
talking about here

00:30:15.584 --> 00:30:19.770
is the idea of having organic
ecosystems that just grow,

00:30:19.770 --> 00:30:22.620
and that you can let die down in
winter, and they come back up.

00:30:22.620 --> 00:30:26.960
And there's that cycle,
that natural cycle, and yet

00:30:26.960 --> 00:30:28.610
feel like they've
been there forever.

00:30:28.610 --> 00:30:31.280
That bottom one is
a Chelsea garden.

00:30:31.280 --> 00:30:32.990
You know, you'd never think--

00:30:32.990 --> 00:30:35.682
it looks like it's in the
middle of the Provence.

00:30:35.682 --> 00:30:37.640
And so there's a few
different planting styles,

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:39.140
and I'll just go through them
really quickly, because they're

00:30:39.140 --> 00:30:40.754
all in the book.

00:30:40.754 --> 00:30:42.420
And there's so many
of them in the book,

00:30:42.420 --> 00:30:45.720
and I've pulled out like
four or five of them.

00:30:45.720 --> 00:30:47.480
And basically, the
cottage-style planting,

00:30:47.480 --> 00:30:50.835
which is that real old English,
formal style, and looks

00:30:50.835 --> 00:30:52.460
like it's kind of
been scattered there.

00:30:52.460 --> 00:30:54.412
But it's actually
pretty high maintenance,

00:30:54.412 --> 00:30:56.120
because you've got
kind of the box balls,

00:30:56.120 --> 00:30:59.150
and all the
perennials dying down,

00:30:59.150 --> 00:31:01.070
and the bulbs that
have to be taken up,

00:31:01.070 --> 00:31:04.100
and all that kind of stuff.

00:31:04.100 --> 00:31:06.860
Modernist-style planting,
which is very clean, very

00:31:06.860 --> 00:31:08.510
modern-- a lot of
that gets combined

00:31:08.510 --> 00:31:11.600
with kind of naturalistic,
kind of wild meadow planting,

00:31:11.600 --> 00:31:12.710
which works really well.

00:31:12.710 --> 00:31:14.450
You can see the top one
there is a Chelsea garden,

00:31:14.450 --> 00:31:15.700
and they've kind of done that.

00:31:18.510 --> 00:31:19.900
That's the
naturalistic planting,

00:31:19.900 --> 00:31:22.210
which really echoes what's
happening in nature.

00:31:22.210 --> 00:31:24.130
And the idea of
naturalistic planting

00:31:24.130 --> 00:31:28.450
is that it does just scatter and
grow and evolve into something

00:31:28.450 --> 00:31:30.670
fresh and new, and
that has really

00:31:30.670 --> 00:31:34.720
been a focus on planting styles
in the past 10 years or so.

00:31:34.720 --> 00:31:40.090
That it's gone away from that
uber planned and maintained

00:31:40.090 --> 00:31:43.720
idea to a more kind of letting
nature do what it wants to do

00:31:43.720 --> 00:31:44.950
and embracing that.

00:31:47.650 --> 00:31:50.380
So that brings me back to
the core of what we do.

00:31:50.380 --> 00:31:53.140
And just if there's
anything that I'd

00:31:53.140 --> 00:31:56.380
love you guys to go away
with today after the talk

00:31:56.380 --> 00:31:59.860
is that connection between,
first of all, everything

00:31:59.860 --> 00:32:03.010
that we do as
people, whether it's

00:32:03.010 --> 00:32:05.530
garden design or
an online platform

00:32:05.530 --> 00:32:11.129
or any other creative or
design-based endeavor,

00:32:11.129 --> 00:32:12.670
that there is always
that connection.

00:32:12.670 --> 00:32:15.250
And the connection is the
person and the experience.

00:32:15.250 --> 00:32:21.510
And much like garden design,
everything is personal,

00:32:21.510 --> 00:32:25.440
and to keep that
connection in mind.

00:32:25.440 --> 00:32:26.255
Thank you.

